Yes, both are excellent books highly relevant to your work in enterprise architecture and distributed systems!

Team Topologies (Matthew Skelton & Manuel Pais, 2019) introduces a model for organizing software teams around four team types — Stream-aligned, Platform, Enabling, and Complicated Subsystem — and three interaction modes (Collaboration, X-as-a-Service, Facilitating). The core idea is that Conway's Law is real and unavoidable, so you should deliberately design your team structure to match the architecture you want to build. Key concepts include cognitive load as a first-class constraint, and the idea of "team-first thinking."

Accelerate (Nicole Forsgren, Jez Humble, Gene Kim, 2018) is grounded in 4 years of DORA research data. It identifies the four key metrics of software delivery performance — Deployment Frequency, Lead Time for Changes, Mean Time to Restore, and Change Failure Rate — and connects them to organizational outcomes. It also covers the technical and cultural practices (like trunk-based development, loosely coupled architecture, and psychological safety) that predict high performance.

The two books complement each other well: Accelerate tells you what outcomes to optimize for and what practices drive them, while Team Topologies tells you how to structure teams to enable those practices at scale.

Given your work on modernizing a monolithic workflow system toward event-driven microservices, both are directly applicable — especially the Team Topologies concepts around platform teams and reducing cognitive load when splitting domains, and Accelerate's emphasis on loosely coupled architecture as a prerequisite for deployment independence.

