Claude responded: Great question — this gets right to the heart of how Team Topologies applies to a modular monolith context.

Great question — this gets right to the heart of how Team Topologies applies to a modular monolith context.

Short answer: Yes, ideally each team owns a set of modules aligned to a business domain. But the nuance matters a lot.

The ideal state

In a well-structured modular monolith, you'd map it like this:

    Team A owns modules for, say, Loan Origination domain
    Team B owns modules for Servicing / Payments domain
    Team C owns modules for Reporting / Analytics domain

Each team has end-to-end ownership — they write the code, define the APIs/interfaces between modules, review PRs, and are on-call for their domain. This is exactly the Stream-aligned team pattern from Team Topologies.

Why this works well for a modular monolith

    The module boundaries become the team boundaries — enforcing Conway's Law deliberately
    Teams develop deep domain expertise over time
    Cognitive load stays manageable because each team only needs to deeply understand their slice
    It sets you up naturally for a future microservices extraction if you ever go that route — the module boundary is already the service boundary

The hard realities though

A few things make this messy in practice:

    Cross-cutting concerns — things like security, auditing, shared utilities don't belong to any one team. This is where a Platform team comes in, owning shared infrastructure and common modules.
    Module boundaries may not be clean yet — in many monoliths, the domains are tangled. Teams end up stepping on each other's modules. This is where an Enabling team (or an architecture guild) helps untangle things and establish clean boundaries before full ownership is assigned.
    Shared database — even if code modules are separate, if teams share the same schema/tables, you still get tight coupling. True team autonomy requires schema ownership too, not just code ownership.
    Interaction modes matter — when Team A needs something from Team B's module, do they submit a PR? File a ticket? Call an API? Team Topologies would say this interaction should be well-defined — ideally X-as-a-Service (consume the module's interface, don't reach into its internals).

Connecting to your context

Given your workflow system with multiple domains, the question I'd ask is: are your current module boundaries driven by business domains, or by technical layers (controllers, services, repos)?

If it's the latter — layered architecture — then team ownership gets really awkward because every feature touches every layer across teams. Domain-driven module boundaries are the prerequisite to clean team ownership.

