The book actually addresses this scenario. You can't just declare team ownership overnight when the codebase doesn't support it yet. The recommended path is roughly:

Phase 1 — Identify domain seams Even in the legacy monolith, start mapping which code logically belongs to which domain. You won't restructure it immediately, but you establish intended ownership on paper. This is where Domain-Driven Design's concept of Bounded Contexts is really useful alongside Team Topologies.

Phase 2 — Strangle the monolith gradually New features go into the clean new modules/services. Legacy code gets refactored or wrapped over time. The Strangler Fig pattern — you're probably already doing this instinctively with your new separate services.

Phase 3 — Harden team boundaries As the new modules/services grow and legacy shrinks, team ownership becomes cleaner and more enforceable.

Practical team ownership in your hybrid state

Given three teams in a mixed codebase, a pragmatic split might be:

    Each team owns specific new modules/services outright — full autonomy there
    Legacy monolith is shared but partitioned — each team has a "primary zone" in the legacy code, but everyone recognizes it's messier and requires more coordination
    One team (or a rotating role) acts as platform/enabler — handling shared infrastructure, CI/CD, database migrations, cross-cutting concerns

The key insight from Accelerate here is: don't wait for perfect architecture to assign ownership. Even loose ownership with acknowledged overlap is better than no ownership, because it creates accountability and starts driving the right behaviors.

