What's actually happening here

This is the classic "Shotgun Surgery" + Knowledge Fragmentation problem, made worse by team and product owner turnover.

The core issue is:

    Complex domain logic (user roles, permissions, status-based rules, task dependencies) lives in one area of the codebase
    That logic was never fully documented or made explicit — it lives in Team 1's heads and in the code
    Team 3 comes in, understands the feature request but not the invariants and rules that must be preserved
    Product Owner only sees the new requirement, not the hidden contracts the existing system enforces
    Deadline pressure means no time to fully explore the impact

The result is working software that broke something else — and often nobody finds out until production.

Why this keeps happening

A few root causes compound each other:

1. No domain ownership The user-roles functionality doesn't "belong" to anyone long-term. Team 1 built it and moved on. Team 3 inherited it temporarily. Nobody is the guardian of that domain's integrity.

2. Business rules are implicit in code The rules like "can't delete a user assigned to an active task" or "only certain roles can be added at certain statuses" — these are business invariants buried in service layer code. They're not documented, not tested comprehensively, and invisible to a new team.

3. Product Owners work vertically, not horizontally Each PO understands their enhancement in isolation. Nobody owns the horizontal view of how the domain behaves across all scenarios. This is a structural gap.

4. No automated safety net If there were comprehensive tests covering all the role/status/task-dependency rules, Team 3 would have gotten failing tests immediately when they broke something. Without that net, breakage is discovered late or in production.

What Team Topologies and Accelerate say about this

Team Topologies would call this a missing domain ownership problem. The user-roles/permissions area is complex enough that it arguably needs a Complicated Subsystem team — a small group that deeply understands this logic and acts as guardians. Other teams consume it as a service rather than directly modifying it.

Accelerate would point to the lack of loosely coupled architecture — if Team 3 modifying one feature can break unrelated functionality, the modules are too tightly coupled and the test coverage is insufficient.

Practical things that could prevent this

Short term:

    Before any team touches a complex domain area, require an impact analysis — map what rules/invariants exist before writing a single line of code
    The original team (Team 1) does a knowledge handoff session to Team 3, not just a code walkthrough but a rules and edge cases walkthrough
    PO sign-off should require explicit confirmation of what existing behavior must be preserved

Medium term:

    Write domain rule documentation for complex areas — not code comments, but actual human-readable business rule definitions. Something like "A user in role X cannot be removed if they are assigned to an open task of type Y"
    Build regression test suites around these rules so any future team gets immediate feedback

Longer term:

    Move toward explicit domain ownership — even in a hybrid monolith, designate which team is the custodian of each complex domain area
    Any other team touching that area works in collaboration mode with the owning team, not independently

The deeper irony here is that the PO driving Team 3's work probably thought they were delivering value. And they did — but they also unknowingly destroyed value elsewhere. That's not a people failure, it's a system and process failure that makes this outcome almost inevitable.

