What 5 years of 100m sprints creates

The knowledge landscape ends up looking like this:

    Tribal knowledge silos — certain developers are the only ones who truly understand certain areas. When they leave or move teams, that knowledge walks out the door
    Tech leads are deep but narrow — they're experts in what their team built, but have blind spots everywhere else
    No single person has the full picture — not the architect, not the PO, not the tech lead. The system's true behavior exists only in the code itself
    The codebase becomes the only source of truth — and it's not human-readable documentation

This is sometimes called the "bus factor" problem — how many people would need to leave before a critical area becomes unmaintainable? In many legacy enterprise apps, that number is 1 or 2 for the most complex domains.

The specific danger in your user-roles example

Think about what actually happened:

Original developer who designed the role-deletion logic
→ probably left or moved to another area
→ took the "why" with them

Code remained but the reasoning behind it was lost
→ why can't you delete a user assigned to a task?
→ was that a business rule or just how it was implemented?
→ nobody knows for certain anymore

Team 3 sees the code but not the intent
→ they work around it or reimplement it differently
→ production breaks

The code captured the what but lost the why. And the why is what prevents future teams from breaking it.

This is bigger than a tech problem

What you're really describing is an organizational knowledge management failure. And honestly most enterprises don't treat knowledge as an asset the same way they treat code or infrastructure.

Consider the asymmetry:

    Code is versioned, tracked, reviewed via PRs
    Infrastructure is documented, managed via IaC
    Business rules and domain knowledge — stored in people's heads, Confluence pages nobody reads, or implicit in code behavior

That asymmetry is what's killing you in production.

What can realistically be done given your constraints

I want to be practical here because "document everything" is not a real answer when every sprint is a 100m race.

The 20% effort that gives 80% protection:

1. Identify your highest-risk domains right now Not the whole app — just the 3-4 areas that are most complex, most frequently touched by multiple teams, and most likely to cause production incidents. Your user-roles/permissions area sounds like one. Create a short list.

2. For each high-risk domain — write a "Domain Rules Card" Not a full specification. Just a one or two page document that captures:

    What are the core invariants? (user can't be deleted if assigned to open task)
    What status-based rules exist?
    What are the known edge cases that have caused bugs before?
    Who has the most context on this area?

This takes maybe half a day per domain if you pull the right people into a room. It's not perfect documentation — it's a crash course card for the next team that touches it.

3. Mark high-risk areas in the codebase itself A simple annotation or README in the module folder:

⚠️ HIGH COMPLEXITY DOMAIN
