Claude responded: This is not Agile.

This is not Agile. This is Agile in name only — and it's one of the most common and damaging misapplications of the framework in enterprise settings.

What's actually happening

What you're describing has a specific name — "Fake Agile" or sometimes called "Dark Scrum" (Ron Jeffries, one of the original Agile Manifesto authors, actually coined that term and deeply regrets how Scrum has been misused).

The pattern looks like:

Waterfall thinking at the top
→ business commits to deadlines without consulting teams
→ POs receive work last minute from above
→ POs dump it on teams last minute
→ Teams are pressured to commit anyway
→ Called "Agile" because there are two-week sprints

The sprint ceremony exists. The Agile principles don't.

What real Agile actually requires

The Scrum Guide is explicit about things your environment is violating:

    Sprint Planning requires a refined backlog — stories should be understood, estimated, and ready before sprint planning, not the day before
    Sprint scope is locked — mid-sprint injections are explicitly an anti-pattern. The Sprint Goal should be protected
    Teams pull work, work isn't pushed — teams commit to what they believe they can deliver, not what management dictates
    Definition of Ready — stories shouldn't enter a sprint unless they meet criteria like acceptance criteria defined, dependencies identified, design questions answered

None of that is happening in your environment.

The real-world consequences you're living

This fake Agile pattern directly causes everything you described earlier:

    Last minute stories → no time for impact analysis → Team 3 breaks what Team 1 built
    Mid-sprint injections → context switching → half-finished work, increased defect rate
    No refinement time → complex domain rules never get discussed → developers discover complexity mid-sprint → shortcuts taken → production incidents
    Deadline pressure → testing compressed or skipped → technical debt accelerates
    Repeated across 5 years → accumulated knowledge debt + technical debt + production instability

Each sprint feels like putting out fires. Because it is.

Why this is hard to fix

The root cause is usually not the development teams or even the POs. It's typically:

    Business stakeholders who don't understand or respect sprint boundaries
    Middle management who over-promise delivery dates to leadership without consulting teams
    POs caught in the middle — pressured from above, expected to deliver below
    No Scrum Master or a weak one — the SM's primary job is to protect the team from exactly this. If that role is absent or filled by someone without authority, the team is unprotected

The teams absorb all the dysfunction and get blamed for quality issues that were structurally inevitable.

What can realistically change

Given you're not at the top of the org chart, full process transformation probably isn't in your hands. But there are things that can be pushed at different levels:

At the team/lead level — things you can influence now:

    Establish a Definition of Ready — even informally. If a story arrives without acceptance criteria or with unresolved questions, the team formally flags it as not ready. Creates visibility even if it doesn't always stop the work
    Document mid-sprint injections — every time a story is injected mid-sprint, log it. Over time this data tells a story to leadership about why velocity is unpredictable and quality suffers
    Time-box the chaos — if a mid-sprint injection is unavoidable, make it explicit that something else gets dropped. Force the trade-off conversation rather than silently absorbing it

At the PO/management level — things worth escalating:

    Production incidents have a cost. If you can connect the pattern — last minute story → no impact analysis → production break → X hours of firefighting — that's a business case for process change
    Most business stakeholders respond to cost and risk language more than process language

The framing that sometimes works:

Don't say "we need better Agile practices." Say "our current intake process is directly causing production incidents and here's the evidence."

The deeper truth

What you're experiencing is a delivery machine that's optimized for the appearance of speed while actually going slower due to rework, production incidents, and accumulated debt.

Real Agile is actually faster — because small batches, clear ownership, protected sprints, and proper refinement eliminate the rework cycle. But it requires discipline and organizational trust that takes time to build.

The irony is that the business thinks they're going faster by pushing last minute stories and mid-sprint changes. They're actually paying for each story two or three times — once to build it, once to fix what it broke, and once in the lost productivity of firefighting.

How receptive is your leadership to hearing this kind of systemic feedback? Is there any appetite for process change, or is it purely delivery-focused at the top?
