Claude responded: Yes, that's actually a well-established best practice — and your agile coaches are giving solid advice.

Yes, that's actually a well-established best practice — and your agile coaches are giving solid advice.

Why 2 sprints ahead is the right target

The idea comes from the concept of a "ready backlog buffer." If you only have the current sprint's stories ready, you're always one surprise away from walking into sprint planning with nothing properly refined. Two sprints of ready stories gives you:

    Breathing room — if a story turns out more complex than expected during refinement, you have time to break it down or get answers before it needs to be sprint-committed
    Flexibility for reprioritization — business can swap priorities between sprint 1 and sprint 2 without blowing up the process, because both are already refined
    Stable sprint planning — the team walks in knowing what they're committing to, rather than discovering complexity at the planning table

The nuance though

Two sprints ready doesn't mean two sprints locked. This is a common misunderstanding that creates friction with business stakeholders. The framing matters:

    "Ready" means the story is understood, sized, and has clear acceptance criteria — not that it's unchangeable
    Business can still reprioritize between ready stories freely
    What they can't do is inject a brand new, unrefined story and expect it to go in next sprint

So the ask to management is really: "Give us a two-sprint refinement runway so we can always walk into planning with stories that are properly understood."

Where it breaks down in practice

The two-sprint buffer only works if:

    Refinement sessions are protected time — not squeezed out by firefighting or delivery pressure
    POs are engaged in refinement — if they're too busy to attend, stories sit in limbo
    Business stakeholders respect the buffer — last-minute priority changes that bypass the ready queue still break the system

In your environment specifically, the bigger risk is #3. Even with a two-sprint buffer, if a VP can still walk in and demand something be done this sprint, the buffer gets bypassed and you're back to the same problem.

So yes, validate your agile coaches on this one — two sprints of ready stories is the right ask. The harder conversation with your new management is making sure they understand that protecting that buffer is their responsibility too, not just the team's.
