What actually happened technically

This is a stale state / incomplete transition bug. The logic probably looks something like:

if category == OTHER:
    hide fields A, B, C on the UI
    // but never actually cleared the data behind them

The UI gave the user the impression that those fields and associated records were gone. But the data persisted silently in the backend. Then when the uniqueness validation ran elsewhere, it correctly fired — because the association was still there, just invisible to the user.

Nobody wrote bad code here. The original developer handled the "Other" category display correctly. What they didn't anticipate was the state transition scenario — a user changing from Cat A to Other after already having associated records.

Why nobody caught it

This scenario requires a very specific sequence:

    Select Cat A
    Fill fields
    Associate a record
    Then change to Other category
    Then try to associate that same record elsewhere

That's a multi-step user journey that only surfaces in real usage patterns. It's almost impossible to catch in a standard sprint test cycle unless someone specifically maps out all valid state transitions for that domain.

And that mapping — the state transition diagram for category changes — almost certainly never existed as a documented artifact. It lived in the original developer's head.

How this connects to everything we discussed

This single bug is a case study in all four root causes:

No domain ownership — the category/field logic was built by someone long gone. Nobody currently owns the "what happens when category changes" behavior as their responsibility to understand and protect.

Implicit business rules — the rule "changing category must clear all category-specific data and associations" was never written down. It was an assumption the original developer made. It wasn't tested as an explicit rule. It wasn't documented anywhere.

PO visibility gap — the PO who accepted the associated-record feature almost certainly never knew about the category-change scenario. They saw "user can associate a record" as a standalone feature, not as something that intersects with category state transitions.

No safety net — if there had been integration tests covering state transitions, one of them would have been: "given a record in Cat A with associations, when user changes to Other, then all Cat A-specific data should be cleared." That test would have caught this. It didn't exist.

The deeper pattern this reveals

This type of bug is actually one of the hardest to prevent because it lives at the intersection of two features — category management and association validation. Neither team that touched those features owned the intersection.

This is what's sometimes called a "feature interaction bug" — each feature works correctly in isolation, but they produce unexpected behavior when combined. And in a 5-year application with dozens of features, the number of possible feature intersections grows faster than any team can manually test.

The only systematic protection against this is:

    State transition documentation for complex domain objects — explicitly mapping what must happen when an entity changes state
    Domain-level integration tests that test transitions, not just happy-path CRUD
    A domain owner who thinks about the whole lifecycle of a record, not just individual features

How to use this example with management

This is a powerful story to tell in your briefing because it's concrete. You can say:

"Here is one specific production incident. The code that caused it had been there for years and was correct. The bug wasn't in any single feature — it was in the transition between two features that were built by different teams at different times, with no one owning the intersection. No one did anything wrong. The system made this outcome inevitable."

That framing — the system made this outcome inevitable — is exactly what you want management to internalize. Because the fix isn't "be more careful." The fix is changing how the system works.

