Claude responded: Yes, your instinct is exactly right.

Yes, your instinct is exactly right. And it's one of the strongest arguments for domain ownership in your management brief.

Why domain ownership directly impacts recovery time

Think about what happens in your current model when a production incident hits:

Incident reported
→ Who owns this? unclear
→ Whoever has bandwidth gets assigned
→ They spend hours just understanding the domain
→ They find the bug
→ They're not sure what else their fix might break
→ Cautious fix takes longer
→ Or rushed fix creates another bug
→ Total time: days

Now compare with a domain ownership model:

Incident reported
→ Domain owning team gets paged
→ They already know the codebase, the rules, the history
→ They find the bug quickly
→ They know exactly what the fix should and shouldn't touch
→ Confident fix deployed fast
→ Total time: hours

The difference isn't developer skill. It's contextual knowledge. And contextual knowledge lives with the team that owns the domain day to day.

This is actually what Accelerate's MTTR metric captures

Mean Time to Restore is one of the four DORA metrics precisely because it reflects organizational capability, not just technical capability. High performing teams restore service in under an hour. Low performing teams take days.

The research found that the biggest predictor of fast MTTR wasn't having better developers. It was clear ownership and psychological safety — people who know the system deeply and aren't afraid to act decisively.

Your current model optimizes for the wrong thing. Assigning whoever has bandwidth feels efficient from a resource utilization perspective. But it's deeply inefficient from a recovery perspective.

The practical reality though

You're right that it's the correct approach. But there are some real challenges to navigate:

Challenge 1 — You don't have clean domain ownership yet

Right now, with a hybrid monolith and no formal ownership model, "the team that owns this domain" may not clearly exist yet. In the short term you need a pragmatic approximation — which team or which individual has the most context on this area? That person gets the call, not whoever is free.

Even an informal "go-to person per domain" list is dramatically better than bandwidth-based assignment.

Challenge 2 — The owning team may be mid-sprint

If Team A owns the record domain and they're deep in sprint work, pulling them onto a production incident disrupts their delivery. This is the tension that makes managers default to "use whoever is free."

The answer is that production incidents should be treated as higher priority than sprint work — but that requires management to explicitly endorse that. If the same manager who demands sprint velocity also demands you don't pull teams off sprint work, the system is contradictory and the team absorbs the pain either way.

Challenge 3 — Knowledge is still concentrated in individuals, not teams

Even within the owning team, the knowledge may sit with one or two specific developers. If they're on leave or unavailable, you're back to the same problem. This is why the Domain Rules Cards and documented state transitions matter — they distribute the knowledge from individuals to the team as a whole.

The test coverage point is equally important

Your instinct about fixing tests is spot on, and it's actually two separate things worth separating:

Fixing the immediate test gap — writing the specific test that would have caught this bug. Fast, targeted, done as part of the hotfix. The domain owning team does this naturally because they understand what to test and why.

Understanding why the test didn't exist — was it a gap in the test strategy? A scenario nobody thought of? This is a quick retrospective question that prevents the same class of bug recurring. A team without domain context will fix the immediate test but miss the broader pattern.

How to frame this for management

The practical ask is simple and concrete:

"When a production incident occurs in a specific domain, the team with the most context on that domain should lead the fix — even if they're mid-sprint. This is not optional. We should maintain a simple map of which team owns which domain so this decision takes seconds, not hours."

Then pair it with: "We will also write a regression test for every production incident as part of the fix. Over 6 months this will measurably reduce the recurrence of the same class of bugs."

Both of those are defensible, practical, and something a new manager can visibly champion. It shows them a concrete way to improve production stability without a massive transformation program.

The bottom line

Your mental model is correct. Domain ownership doesn't just prevent bugs — it dramatically shrinks recovery time when bugs do happen. And in a two-week sprint world where some bugs will always reach production, fast recovery is arguably more valuable than perfect prevention.

The team that built it, understands it, owns it — and can fix it fastest. That's not just intuition. The research backs it up.
