PR approved by two leads	Senior eyes catch what junior missed	Slows delivery, leads become rubber stamps over time

They all share the same waterfall DNA:

"If we add more checkpoints at the end, we'll catch more problems."

The Agile and DevOps research says the opposite — move quality left, not right. Catch problems when they're cheap to fix, not when they're expensive.

Why the two-lead PR approval is particularly painful

The other three at least have some theoretical quality benefit. The two-lead PR approval has a specific set of real-world failure modes:

It creates false confidence Leads are busy. When a PR sits in the queue, the path of least resistance is to approve it to keep things moving. Over time "approved by two leads" becomes a rubber stamp, not a real review. But now everyone believes it was properly reviewed.

It punishes good teams and doesn't fix bad ones A team with strong engineering practices and good test coverage gets slowed down by mandatory dual approval. A team with poor practices just gets two approvals on bad code.

It doesn't scale with growth Two leads reviewing every PR means leads spend a growing percentage of their time in code review. As the team grows, this becomes a full-time job. Leads stop doing architecture and strategy work because they're buried in PRs.

It addresses the symptom, not the cause The reason leads feel they need to review everything is because they don't trust the system — no tests, no domain ownership, inconsistent practices. The fix is building that trust through better practices, not adding a gate that papers over the lack of trust.

The deeper truth about all four

These responses come from a place of genuine concern. Senior management and leads want quality. They're not wrong to want it. They're wrong about how to get it.

The instinct is: "more eyes, more gates, more checkpoints = more quality."

The reality is: "quality comes from building it in from the start — clear ownership, good practices, fast feedback, and psychological safety to raise concerns early."

Accelerate's research is unambiguous on this. The highest performing engineering organizations have fewer bureaucratic approval processes, not more. They compensate with better automated testing, clear ownership, and strong engineering culture.

