Claude responded: Great context — this is a very common setup in legacy enterprise Java/Spring environments.

Great context — this is a very common setup in legacy enterprise Java/Spring environments. Let me break this into two parts.

Part 1 — Integration Testing Without Testcontainers or Individual DBs

Given your constraints — shared dev DB, no Docker, embedded Tomcat locally — you have a few realistic options.

Option 1 — H2 In-Memory Database for Integration Tests

This is the most practical starting point with zero infrastructure change.

Spring Boot supports H2 as a drop-in for Oracle/MySQL during tests. You configure a separate test application properties:
properties

# src/test/resources/application-test.properties
spring.datasource.url=jdbc:h2:mem:testdb;MODE=Oracle
spring.datasource.driver-class-name=org.h2.Driver
spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=create-drop

Then annotate your integration tests:
java

@SpringBootTest
@ActiveProfiles("test")
@Transactional // rolls back after each test - keeps DB clean
class UserRoleIntegrationTest {

    @Test
    void whenCategoryChangesToOther_thenAssociationsShouldBeCleared() {
        // the exact scenario that hit production
    }
}

Pros — zero infrastructure, runs on every developer machine, fast, isolated per test run

Cons — H2 doesn't perfectly replicate Oracle behaviour. Complex Oracle-specific queries, stored procedures, or constraints may behave differently. This is the main risk.

Option 2 — Dedicated Integration Test Schema on Shared DB

Since you already have a shared dev DB, ask the DBA to create a separate schema specifically for integration tests:

DEV_SCHEMA      → developers work here manually
INTTEST_SCHEMA  → owned by the pipeline, reset between runs

Your integration test datasource points to INTTEST_SCHEMA. The pipeline:

    Runs Flyway/Liquibase migrations to set up schema
    Runs integration tests
    Truncates or drops/recreates the schema after

Pros — real Oracle behaviour, no H2 compatibility issues, no Docker needed

Cons — shared resource means tests can interfere if run in parallel by multiple people. Best suited for pipeline execution, not local developer runs.

Option 3 — Combine Both

This is actually the most pragmatic approach for your context:

    Developers run H2-based tests locally — fast feedback, no shared resource contention
    Pipeline runs against real Oracle schema — catches any H2/Oracle discrepancies before merge

The test code is identical. Only the datasource config differs per environment.

What to test first

Don't try to write integration tests for everything. Start with your highest-risk domain scenarios — exactly like the category/association bug. Write tests that exercise the state transitions explicitly:
java

@Test
void changingCategoryToOther_shouldClearAllCategorySpecificAssociations() {
    // Given: record with Category A and associated records
    // When: category changed to Other  
    // Then: all Category A associations are cleared
}

@Test
void associatingSameRecord_toMultipleActiveRecords_shouldFail() {
    // the uniqueness validation scenario
}

These become your regression safety net — every production incident adds one test here.

Part 2 — Post-Deployment Testing on OpenShift

This is where it gets interesting because OpenShift pipelines give you real power here.

The concept — Smoke Tests as a Pipeline Stage

After your deployment stage completes, add a dedicated post-deployment test stage that runs a lightweight suite of tests against the live deployed environment.

Pipeline stages:
Build → Unit Tests → Deploy to ENV → Post-Deploy Smoke Tests → (Gate) → Promote

If smoke tests fail, the pipeline fails and you know immediately — before anyone notices in production.

How to implement in OpenShift pipelines

You have a few approaches depending on what your pipeline supports:

Approach A — Maven failsafe plugin with a smoke test profile

Create a separate Maven profile for smoke tests that runs against a real URL:
xml

<!-- pom.xml -->
<profile>
    <id>smoke-tests</id>
    <build>
        <plugins>
            <plugin>
                <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
                <artifactId>maven-failsafe-plugin</artifactId>
                <configuration>
                    <includes>
                        <include>**/*SmokeTest.java</include>
                    </includes>
                    <systemPropertyVariables>
                        <app.base.url>${app.base.url}</app.base.url>
                    </systemPropertyVariables>
                </configuration>
            </plugin>
        </plugins>
    </build>
</profile>

Your OpenShift pipeline passes in the deployed URL:
bash

mvn verify -Psmoke-tests -Dapp.base.url=https://your-app.openshift.example.com

Approach B — REST Assured for API-level smoke tests

REST Assured is the most natural fit for Spring Boot API testing:
java

@Tag("smoke")
class PostDeploymentSmokeTest {

    private static final String BASE_URL = System.getProperty("app.base.url");

    @Test
    void healthCheckShouldReturn200() {
        given()
            .baseUri(BASE_URL)
        .when()
            .get("/actuator/health")
        .then()
            .statusCode(200)
            .body("status", equalTo("UP"));
    }

    @Test
    void criticalAPIEndpointShouldRespond() {
        given()
            .baseUri(BASE_URL)
            .header("Authorization", "Bearer " + getTestToken())
        .when()
            .get("/api/records")
        .then()
            .statusCode(200);
    }
}

What your smoke tests should cover

Keep it focused. Smoke tests are not full regression — they verify the deployment succeeded and critical paths are alive:

    Health check — /actuator/health returns UP
    Critical API endpoints — your most used APIs return expected response codes
    Key business workflows — not exhaustive, just the top 3-4 that would indicate a broken deployment
    Database connectivity — an endpoint that proves DB connection is live
    Integration points — if you call external services, verify those connections are alive

Putting it together in OpenShift

A typical Tekton pipeline stage would look like:
yaml

- name: smoke-test
  taskRef:
    name: maven
  params:
    - name: GOALS
      value:
        - verify
        - -Psmoke-tests
        - -Dapp.base.url=$(params.APP_URL)
  runAfter:
    - deploy

The key pipeline design principle: smoke test failure should block promotion to the next environment. If it fails in DEV, it doesn't go to UAT. If it fails in UAT, it doesn't go to PROD.

Realistic roadmap for your environment

Given where you are today, a practical sequence would be:

Sprint 1-2 — Set up H2-based integration tests locally. Write 5-10 tests covering your highest-risk domain scenarios. Get them running in the existing pipeline as a build gate.

Sprint 3-4 — Add a dedicated integration test schema to the shared DB. Run the same tests against real Oracle in the pipeline. Fix any H2/Oracle discrepancies found.

Sprint 5-6 — Add post-deployment smoke tests. Wire them into the OpenShift pipeline as a gate after deployment.

Ongoing — Every production incident adds at least one new integration test or smoke test. Over 6 months this compounds into a meaningful safety net.

The most important thing is starting somewhere rather than waiting for perfect infrastructure. Even 10 well-chosen integration tests around your riskiest domain scenarios would have caught your category/association bug before it reached production.
